2022-08-05 14:54 EDT Chief Complaint Abdominal swelling with chest and epigastric pain for "a while". .

History of Present Illness
Patient presents with complaint of swollen abdomen times years and then epigastric pain onset last night. States she had a normal day yesterday. She also states she has a mild cough and she feels like the epigastric pain radiates into her chest. She says that sometimes she has some shortness of breath but presently she is not short of breath she has a history of asthma and states she has been taking her nebulizer. She states the pain is severe. Seems to be worse with some movements and she states that she feels like she cannot eat very much she says she gets full after just a few bites of food but she does not have any nausea or vomiting or diarrhea and she has not had a measured fever but she felt hot last night. History does include an esophageal ring and hypertension

Patient's symptoms been going on since last night she had a unremarkable nonischemic appearing EKG and a negative troponin. Her pain is epigastric radiating into the chest and she does have epigastric tenderness. As regards to the shape of her abdomen, I discussed with her that I think that that is just the normal shape of her abdomen as there is no abnormal findings related to ascites or liver or free fluid in the abdomen on her CAT scan. Her CAT scan did show mild inflammation suggestive of diverticulitis. She had a negative chest x-ray and unremarkable labs. Patient has had no vomiting in the ER and I think she is safe to discharge home with oral antibiotics. She already has a GI doctor will have her follow-up with them

Diverticulitis
Diverticulitis is when small pouches in your colon (large intestine) get infected or swollen. This causes pain in the belly (abdomen) and watery poop (diarrhea).
These pouches are called diverticula. The pouches form in people who have a condition called diverticulosis.
What are the causes?
This condition may be caused by poop (stool) that gets trapped in the pouches in your colon. The poop lets germs (bacteria) grow in the pouches. This causes the infection.
What increases the risk?
You are more likely to get this condition if you have small pouches in your colon. The risk is higher if:
• You are overweight or very overweight (obese).
• You do not exercise enough.
• You drink alcohol.
• You smoke or use products with tobacco in them.
• You eat a diet that has a lot of red meat such as beef, pork, or lamb.
• You eat a diet that does not have enough fiber in it.
• You are older than 40 years of age.
What are the signs or symptoms?
• Pain in the belly. Pain is often on the left side, but it may be in other areas.
• Fever and feeling cold.
• Feeling like you may vomit.
• Vomiting.
• Having cramps.
• Feeling full.
• Changes to how often you poop.
• Blood in your poop.
How is this treated?
Most cases are treated at home by:
• Taking over-the-counter pain medicines.
• Following a clear liquid diet.
• Taking antibiotic medicines.
• Resting.
Very bad cases may need to be treated at a hospital. This may include:
• Not eating or drinking.
• Taking prescription pain medicine.
• Getting antibiotic medicines through an IV tube.
• Getting fluid and food through an IV tube.
• Having surgery.
When you are feeling better, your doctor may tell you to have a test to check your colon (colonoscopy).
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
• Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your doctor. These include:
◦ Antibiotics.
◦ Pain medicines.
◦ Fiber pills.
◦ Probiotics.
◦ Stool softeners.
• If you were prescribed an antibiotic medicine, take it as told by your doctor. Do not stop taking the antibiotic even if you start to feel better.
• Ask your doctor if the medicine prescribed to you requires you to avoid driving or using machinery.
Eating and drinking
• Follow a diet as told by your doctor.
• When you feel better, your doctor may tell you to change your diet. You may need to eat a lot of fiber. Fiber makes it easier to poop (have a bowel movement). Foods with fiber include:
◦ Berries.
◦ Beans.
◦ Lentils.
◦ Green vegetables.
• Avoid eating red meat.
General instructions
• Do not use any products that contain nicotine or tobacco, such as cigarettes, e-cigarettes, and chewing tobacco. If you need help quitting, ask your doctor.
• Exercise 3 or more times a week. Try to get 30 minutes each time. Exercise enough to sweat and make your heart beat faster.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
Contact a doctor if:
• Your pain does not get better.
• You are not pooping like normal.
Get help right away if:
• Your pain gets worse.
• Your symptoms do not get better.
• Your symptoms get worse very fast.
• You have a fever.
• You vomit more than one time.
• You have poop that is:
◦ Bloody.
◦ Black.
◦ Tarry.
Summary
• This condition happens when small pouches in your colon get infected or swollen.
• Take medicines only as told by your doctor.
• Follow a diet as told by your doctor.
• Keep all follow-up visits as told by your doctor. This is important.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
